                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. DPIIT Recognition is necessary but NOT sufficient for Section 80-IAC. The tax holiday requires a SEPARATE Form 80IAC application reviewed by the Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB). As of 2026, only approximately 3,700 of 2.07 lakh DPIIT-recognised startups have received IMB certificates - an approval rate of approximately 1.8 percent. The IMB applies materially higher scrutiny than DPIIT itself." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB) and how does it differ from DPIIT recognition?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The IMB is a board constituted by DPIIT with representatives from various ministries; it separately evaluates Form 80IAC applications for Section 80-IAC tax exemption based on innovation depth, scalability, employment generation and wealth creation potential. The 120-day review window applies per the April 2025 revised framework. DPIIT recognition is the broad gateway; IMB certification is the narrow tax-holiday qualification." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Can a Partnership Firm or Sole Proprietorship get DPIIT Recognition?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Registered Partnership Firm - YES; Sole Proprietorship - NO. Under G.S.R. 108(E) 2026, eligible entity types are Pvt Ltd, LLP, registered Partnership Firm and Cooperative. Sole proprietorships are NOT eligible. A proprietor must first restructure to Pvt Ltd, LLP or Partnership Firm before applying. Even Partnership Firms cannot access Section 80-IAC tax holiday (restricted to Pvt Ltd and LLP only) - though they can access other benefits." }
            },
