<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">DPIIT Startup Recognition in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - DPIIT Startup Recognition Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>DPIIT Startup Recognition is the free Government of India certification under the Startup India scheme - updated by G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026. Eligible entities are Pvt Ltd, LLP, Partnership Firm and Cooperative; under 10 years from incorporation; turnover under INR 200 crore. Recognition takes 7 to 14 days. DPIIT is necessary but NOT sufficient for Section 80-IAC tax holiday - that requires a separate IMB application.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Framework</td><td>Startup India scheme (16 Jan 2016) + Notification G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026 + Section 80-IAC Income Tax Act 1961 + Section 56(2)(viib) ABOLISHED by Finance (No. 2) Act 2024 from 1 April 2025</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Pvt Ltd, LLP, Registered Partnership Firm or Cooperative; under 10 years from incorporation; turnover under INR 200 crore; innovation OR scalable model OR Deep Tech research; NOT formed by splitting up / reconstruction</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>DPIIT Recognition 7 to 14 days (some clean apps in 72 hours); Section 80-IAC IMB up to 120 days separately</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 4,499 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges); DPIIT government fee ZERO</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 80-IAC Tax Holiday</td><td>100% deduction for any 3 consecutive years out of first 10; SEPARATE Form 80IAC + IMB approval; ~1.8% approval rate; Pvt Ltd and LLP only</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Incorporation Deadline (80-IAC)</td><td>1 April 2030 (extended by Union Budget 2025-26)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Validity</td><td>Up to 10 years from incorporation OR until turnover crosses INR 200 crore (whichever earlier)</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>The Startup India scheme launched on 16 January 2016 created a regulatory framework that allows eligible Indian startups to access tax holidays, IPR rebates, public procurement preference, easier compliance and funding eligibility - all conditioned on a DPIIT Startup Recognition Certificate. The 2026 framework under G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026 materially widened access - eligible entity types now include Cooperatives (in addition to Private Limited Companies, LLPs and registered Partnership Firms), the turnover threshold was raised from INR 100 crore to INR 200 crore and a dedicated Deep Tech category was created for startups based on fundamental scientific or engineering breakthroughs. The DPIIT Recognition itself is free - zero government fee, fully online via the Startup India portal and approved in 7 to 14 days for clean applications. The critical clarification most founders miss - DPIIT Recognition is necessary but NOT sufficient for the Section 80-IAC tax holiday; that benefit requires a separate Form 80IAC application reviewed by the Inter-Ministerial Board, which has approved only ~3,700 of the 2.07 lakh DPIIT-recognised startups (an approval rate of approximately 1.8 percent as of 2026). Patron Accounting's Delhi office runs the DPIIT application at INR 4,499 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges).</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What DPIIT Startup Recognition Actually Is</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>DPIIT Startup Recognition is the Government of India certification that an eligible entity qualifies as a "startup" under the Startup India framework. The Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT) issues the recognition through the Startup India portal under the framework currently set by G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026. Recognition makes the entity eligible to apply for the larger set of Startup India benefits - tax holiday under Section 80-IAC of the Income Tax Act 1961, patent and trademark fee rebates, public procurement preference on GeM, Startup India Seed Fund Scheme (SISFS) eligibility, Fund of Funds for Startups (FFS) routing via SIDBI, self-certification under 9 labour laws and 3 environment laws and fast-track winding up under Section 55 of the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code 2016.</p>

<p>The most important practical clarification - <strong>DPIIT Recognition is the GATEWAY but NOT the destination.</strong> The Section 80-IAC tax holiday (100% income tax exemption on profits for any 3 consecutive years out of the first 10 years from incorporation) requires a SEPARATE Form 80IAC application reviewed by the Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB). The IMB has a 120-day review window and approves applications based on innovation quality, scalability, employment generation and wealth creation potential. As of 2026, only approximately 3,700 of 2.07 lakh DPIIT-recognised startups have IMB certificates (an approval rate of about 1.8 percent per PIB Press Release PRID 2227597 dated 12 February 2026). DPIIT Recognition itself is free, fast and broad - the strategic value lies in framing the underlying innovation case strongly during DPIIT application, so that the subsequent IMB application has a stronger substantive base.</p>

<p>Delhi anchors DPIIT engagements because the DPIIT itself is headquartered in Vanijya Bhawan, New Delhi - direct proximity to the nodal agency, the IMB secretariat and the wider Startup India ecosystem (TiE Delhi-NCR, NASSCOM, FICCI startup committees, the Income-tax Department's central charge for startup claims). Patron's Delhi office runs the application from one engagement.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for DPIIT Startup Recognition:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>DPIIT:</strong> Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade, Ministry of Commerce and Industry; nodal agency for Startup India.</p>
<p><strong>DPIIT Recognition Certificate:</strong> Government certification of startup status; free, online, 7-14 days; valid up to 10 years from incorporation or until turnover crosses INR 200 crore.</p>
<p><strong>G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026:</strong> Current Notification governing DPIIT Recognition framework - expanded entity eligibility (Cooperative added), raised turnover threshold (INR 200 crore), Deep Tech category.</p>
<p><strong>Section 80-IAC Income Tax Act 1961:</strong> 100% income tax exemption on profits for any 3 consecutive years out of first 10; available only to Pvt Ltd and LLP; SEPARATE Form 80IAC + IMB approval.</p>
<p><strong>Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB):</strong> Constituted by DPIIT; evaluates Form 80IAC; 120-day review window; ~1.8% approval rate.</p>
<p><strong>Deep Tech Category (2026):</strong> Startups based on fundamental scientific or engineering breakthroughs - semiconductors, advanced materials, biotech, quantum, fusion, robotics, AI/ML core research.</p>
<p><strong>SISFS:</strong> Startup India Seed Fund Scheme - INR 945 crore corpus via approved incubators.</p>
<p><strong>FFS:</strong> Fund of Funds for Startups - INR 10,000 crore via SIDBI to AIFs.</p>
<p><strong>GeM Procurement Preference:</strong> Exemption from prior turnover and experience criteria and from Earnest Money Deposit (EMD).</p>
<p><strong>Section 56(2)(viib) Abolished:</strong> Angel Tax abolished by Finance (No. 2) Act 2024 from 1 April 2025 - no longer a DPIIT benefit angle for fresh transactions.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
