<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Startups Should Get DPIIT Recognition (and Which Should Not Bother)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>DPIIT Recognition is HIGH-ROI for the following Delhi-NCR startup profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Pvt Ltd or LLP startups under 10 years with clear innovation evidence:</strong> Section 80-IAC tax holiday alone justifies the recognition effort even at the ~1.8% IMB approval rate - upside is material for the 1.8% who qualify.</li>
                    <li><strong>Patent-filing startups (especially Deep Tech, biotech, semiconductors, robotics):</strong> The 80% patent fee rebate is meaningful when filing 5-10+ patents per year over the early-stage runway.</li>
                    <li><strong>Startups bidding for PSU and large corporate tenders:</strong> DPIIT-recognised status removes prior turnover and experience qualification barriers; exempts from Earnest Money Deposit on GeM.</li>
                    <li><strong>Startups seeking SISFS funding:</strong> DPIIT recognition is a hard prerequisite for incubator-routed seed-stage funding (INR 945 crore corpus).</li>
                    <li><strong>Startups seeking AIF-routed funding under FFS:</strong> AIF managers prioritise DPIIT-recognised startups as part of their LP-mandate compliance with FFS.</li>
                    <li><strong>Labour-law-heavy sectors (manufacturing, construction, contract labour):</strong> 5-year self-certification eliminates inspection-driven compliance overhead under 9 labour and 3 environment laws.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>Limited value for:</strong> Sole Proprietorships (NOT eligible - must restructure to Pvt Ltd, LLP or Partnership Firm first); service businesses with no clear innovation angle and no patent / trademark pipeline; startups already over 10 years or already past INR 200 crore turnover; startups formed by splitting up or reconstruction of existing business; Partnership Firms expecting Section 80-IAC (restricted to Pvt Ltd and LLP only); founders chasing only the angel tax benefit (Section 56(2)(viib) was abolished from 1 April 2025).</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

