<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>DPIIT scrutiny notes on innovation evidence</td><td>Particularly common for service businesses where the "innovation" framing is weak or generic; rejection rate goes up when the innovation note merely restates the business model without identifying a specific differentiator.</td><td>Patron frames the innovation note with three specific components - (a) what the startup does differently from existing alternatives, (b) the customer outcome that improves measurably as a result and (c) the defensibility of the difference (technology, process, IP or business model). For service businesses, focus on process innovation, technology-enabled service delivery or data network effects.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Splitting up / reconstruction exclusion</td><td>A startup formed by carving out part of an existing business cannot qualify under DPIIT framework; this catches many corporate spin-outs and family business restructurings.</td><td>Patron assesses this at engagement start - examining founders' prior business activities, source of initial assets / IP / customers / revenue and legal structure of any prior business. Where carve-out characteristics exist, the entity origination story is restructured (clear new IP creation, independent customer acquisition, independent funding) before applying.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 80-IAC IMB approval rate of ~1.8 percent</td><td>Founders often expect DPIIT Recognition to automatically grant tax holiday, but the IMB applies materially higher scrutiny than DPIIT itself - only 3,700 of 2.07 lakh recognised startups have IMB certificates as of February 2026.</td><td>Patron does a pre-application substance check for 80-IAC before drafting Form 80IAC - assessing innovation depth, scalability evidence, employment projections and wealth creation potential against the IMB's revised April 2025 evaluation framework. Where substance is borderline, defer the 80-IAC application by 12-24 months to build stronger evidence.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 56(2)(viib) Angel Tax abolition</td><td>Founders chasing only this benefit no longer find it - abolished by Finance (No. 2) Act 2024 from 1 April 2025; legacy assessments for pre-1-April-2024 transactions continue under old law and need defence.</td><td>Patron clarifies expectations at engagement start - no Section 56(2)(viib) issue arises for fresh equity rounds at premium above FMV from 1 April 2024 onwards. For legacy assessments still under scrutiny, DPIIT recognition continues to support the defence; Patron offers separate Angel Tax legacy assessment defence.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Turnover crossing INR 200 crore mid-year</td><td>DPIIT recognition ceases to apply once turnover crosses INR 200 crore in any FY; this catches fast-scaling startups by surprise.</td><td>Patron flags the projected turnover trajectory at engagement start and recommends securing all benefits (especially 80-IAC IMB certificate where eligible) BEFORE turnover crosses INR 200 crore. The 80-IAC, once granted, continues to apply for the 3 elected years even if recognition lapses afterwards; benefit timing matters.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sole Proprietorship NOT eligible</td><td>Many founders apply as sole proprietors and get rejected - the four eligible entity types are Pvt Ltd, LLP, registered Partnership Firm and Cooperative under G.S.R. 108(E) 2026.</td><td>Patron screens entity type at engagement intake - sole proprietors are routed first through entity setup (Pvt Ltd via SPICe+ or LLP via FiLLiP, typically 7-10 working days) before applying for DPIIT Recognition. Conversion route also available where business already operates as a proprietorship with goodwill.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

