<!-- SECTION 15A: LEGAL FRAMEWORK -->
<section class="content-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Legal and Compliance Framework</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p><strong>Scheme Launch:</strong> Startup India scheme launched by the Government of India on 16 January 2016.</p>
                <p><strong>Nodal Agency:</strong> Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT), Ministry of Commerce and Industry, Vanijya Bhawan, New Delhi.</p>
                <p><strong>Current Framework Notification:</strong> G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026 - expanded eligibility (Cooperative added), turnover threshold raised to INR 200 crore, Deep Tech category introduced.</p>
                <p><strong>Application Portals:</strong> Startup India portal (<a href="https://www.startupindia.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">startupindia.gov.in</a>) - primary; National Single Window System NSWS portal (<a href="https://www.nsws.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nsws.gov.in</a>) - integrated route.</p>
                <p><strong>Eligibility Criteria:</strong> Entity type - Pvt Ltd / LLP / Registered Partnership Firm / Cooperative; Age - up to 10 years from incorporation; Turnover - below INR 200 crore in any preceding FY; Innovation - working on innovation, development or improvement of products / services / processes OR scalable business model OR Deep Tech research; Not formed by splitting up or reconstruction of an existing business.</p>
                <p><strong>Tax Holiday - Section 80-IAC Income Tax Act 1961:</strong> 100% deduction of profits and gains for any 3 consecutive assessment years out of first 10 from incorporation; SEPARATE Form 80IAC application via Startup India portal; Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB) review; available to Pvt Ltd and LLP ONLY.</p>
                <p><strong>Section 80-IAC Incorporation Deadline:</strong> Eligible startup must be incorporated on or before 1 April 2030 (extended from 1 April 2025 by Union Budget 2025-26).</p>
                <p><strong>IMB Approval Process:</strong> 120-day review window per April 2025 revised framework (effective from 80th IMB meeting on 30 April 2025); ~1.8% approval rate (3,700 of 2.07 lakh DPIIT-recognised startups as of February 2026 per PIB Press Release PRID 2227597).</p>
                <p><strong>Section 56(2)(viib) Angel Tax:</strong> ABOLISHED by Finance (No. 2) Act 2024 with effect from 1 April 2025 (AY 2025-26 onwards).</p>
                <p><strong>Section 54GB Income Tax Act:</strong> Capital gains exemption for individuals / HUFs investing sale proceeds of residential property in equity of an eligible startup.</p>
                <p><strong>Section 79 Carry-Forward Losses:</strong> Special relaxation for eligible startups even with shareholding change above 51% provided all original shareholders continue to hold shares.</p>
                <p><strong>Section 55 IBC Fast-Track Winding Up:</strong> Section 55 of the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code 2016 - target 90 days (extendable to 135 days) versus standard 180-330 day CIRP.</p>
                <p><strong>SISFS:</strong> Startup India Seed Fund Scheme - INR 945 crore corpus via approved incubators.</p>
                <p><strong>FFS:</strong> Fund of Funds for Startups - INR 10,000 crore via SIDBI to SEBI-registered AIFs.</p>
                <p><strong>Authority for source verification:</strong> Startup India portal at <a href="https://www.startupindia.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">startupindia.gov.in</a>, DPIIT website at <a href="https://www.dpiit.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dpiit.gov.in</a> and India Code (statutes) at <a href="https://www.indiacode.nic.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">indiacode.nic.in</a>.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

