                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is DPIIT Startup Recognition and who is eligible?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>DPIIT Startup Recognition is the Government of India certification under the Startup India scheme that an eligible entity qualifies as a startup. Under G.S.R. 108(E) dated 4 February 2026, eligible entities are Private Limited Company, LLP, registered Partnership Firm or Cooperative; under 10 years from incorporation; turnover below INR 200 crore in any preceding FY; working on innovation or a scalable business model; not formed by splitting up or reconstruction of an existing business.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is DPIIT Recognition free? What is the government fee?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes, DPIIT Recognition is completely free - zero government fee. The application is fully online via the Startup India portal (https://www.startupindia.gov.in). Patron Accounting charges INR 4,499 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) as a professional fee for end-to-end application support - eligibility review, innovation note drafting, document compilation, portal submission and certificate delivery.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does DPIIT Startup Recognition approval take in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Typical approval is 7 to 14 days from application submission. Clean applications with strong innovation documentation are sometimes approved within 72 hours. Applications with scrutiny notes from DPIIT take additional time for response and re-review. Patron handles end-to-end submission and tracking within 10 to 20 working days from engagement signing.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are the benefits of DPIIT Startup Recognition?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Gateway to Section 80-IAC tax holiday (3 consecutive years out of first 10 - separate IMB certification needed); 80 percent rebate on patent application fees; 50 percent rebate on trademark fees; self-certification under 9 labour laws and 3 environment laws for 5 years; GeM procurement preference (no prior turnover criteria, no EMD); SISFS and Fund of Funds eligibility; fast-track winding up under Section 55 IBC within 90 days.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Does DPIIT Recognition automatically give Section 80-IAC tax exemption?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. DPIIT Recognition is necessary but NOT sufficient for Section 80-IAC. The tax holiday requires a SEPARATE Form 80IAC application reviewed by the Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB). As of 2026, only approximately 3,700 of 2.07 lakh DPIIT-recognised startups have received IMB certificates - an approval rate of approximately 1.8 percent. The IMB applies materially higher scrutiny than DPIIT itself.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the Inter-Ministerial Board (IMB) and how does it differ from DPIIT recognition?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The IMB is a board constituted by DPIIT with representatives from various ministries; it separately evaluates Form 80IAC applications for Section 80-IAC tax exemption based on innovation depth, scalability, employment generation and wealth creation potential. The 120-day review window applies per the April 2025 revised framework. DPIIT recognition is the broad gateway; IMB certification is the narrow tax-holiday qualification.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can a Partnership Firm or Sole Proprietorship get DPIIT Recognition?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Registered Partnership Firm - YES; Sole Proprietorship - NO. Under G.S.R. 108(E) 2026, eligible entity types are Pvt Ltd, LLP, registered Partnership Firm and Cooperative. Sole proprietorships are NOT eligible. A proprietor must first restructure to Pvt Ltd, LLP or Partnership Firm before applying. Even Partnership Firms cannot access Section 80-IAC tax holiday (restricted to Pvt Ltd and LLP only) - though they can access other benefits.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is Section 56(2)(viib) Angel Tax still a benefit of DPIIT Recognition?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. Section 56(2)(viib) Angel Tax was ABOLISHED by the Finance (No. 2) Act 2024 with effect from 1 April 2025 (AY 2025-26 onwards). Equity issued at premium above FMV on or after 1 April 2024 is no longer chargeable as income in the issuing company. Founders pursuing DPIIT Recognition solely for angel tax benefit no longer find it. Legacy assessments for pre-1-April-2024 transactions continue under the old law.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

